SIMPLE: egret
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Egret
<hw>E"gret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Aigret</er>,
<er>Heron</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld> <def>The name
of several species of herons which bear plumes on the back. They are
generally white. Among the best known species are the American egret
(<spn>Ardea egretta</spn> syn. <spn>Herodias egretta</spn>); the great
egret (<spn>Ardea alba</spn>); the little egret (<spn>Ardea
garzetta</spn>), of Europe; and the American snowy egret (<spn>Ardea
candidissima</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A bunch of <qex>egrets</qex> killed for their plumage.</q>
<rj><qau>G. W. Cable.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A plume or tuft of feathers worn as a part of a
headdress, or anything imitating such an ornament; an
aigrette.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The flying feathery or hairy crown
of seeds or achenes, as the down of the thistle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld> <def>A kind of ape.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Egrette</ent>⟦br⟧
